</div>
<div>
<p><a name="6"></a>[6] While works such as <i>Canada 1812 </i>are often referred to as “graphic novels,” I use the terms “comics” and “comic book” as do many comics scholars. For more on the terminology and theory surrounding the study of comics see, for example, Scott McCloud, <i>Understanding Comics: The Invisible Art </i>(New York 1994); Douglas Wolk, <i>Reading Comics: How Graphic Novels Work and What they Mean</i> (Cambridge 2007); Jeet Heer and Kent Worchester eds., <i>A Comics Studies Reader </i>(Jackson 2009); Sean Carleton, “Drawn to Change: Comics and Critical Consciousness,” <i>Labour/Le Travail</i>, (Spring 2014), Forthcoming.</p>
